# Incident Report — IR-2026-001

**Analyst:** MyMvna
**Date:** May 27, 2026
**Severity:** Medium
**Status:** Resolved

---

## What Happened

I detected an SSH brute force attack against my Linux server during a homelab exercise. The attack came from my Kali Linux VM and generated 328 failed login attempts in about 2 minutes. My Splunk alert caught it almost immediately. No successful logins happened.

---

## Timeline

| Time | What Happened |
|------|---------------|
| T+00:00 | Kali VM started SSH brute force against Oracle Linux target |
| T+02:00 | Splunk alert fired — failed login count hit the threshold I set (>5) |
| T+05:00 | I stopped the attack manually — 328 failed attempts in the logs |
| T+10:00 | Checked logs to confirm no successful logins |
| T+15:00 | Wrote this report |

---

## How I Detected It

I had a Splunk detection rule monitoring `/var/log/secure` on the Linux VM. When failed SSH attempts crossed 5, the alert triggered.

**The search I used:**
```spl
index=main sourcetype=linux_secure "Failed password"
| stats count by host
| where count > 5
```

This ran on a 5-minute schedule. It fired within the first couple minutes of the attack starting.

