## What I'd Do Differently in a Real Environment

| Priority | Action | Why |
|----------|--------|-----|
| High | Set up fail2ban — auto-block after 5 failed attempts | Would've stopped the attack way earlier |
| High | Switch to key-based SSH only, disable password login | Brute force literally can't work without passwords |
| Medium | Tighten the firewall to only allow SSH from trusted IPs | Less exposure overall |
| Medium | Lower alert threshold from 5 to 3 attempts | Catch it even faster |
| Low | Audit all default credentials across every service | Default creds were how my CCDC environment got hit too |

---

## Summary

The detection rule worked exactly as expected. The attack was caught fast, no access was gained, and the logs gave me everything I needed to understand what happened. In a real SOC I'd follow up by blocking the source IP, opening a ticket, and escalating depending on where the traffic was coming from.

